	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=classes2.html?class=7&mid=107538626644707>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=classes2.html?class=7&mid=107538626644707>Pacification</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes2.html?class=7&mid=107538626644707#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Thu, Jan 29th 9:24 AM 2004</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=149003><span id=Guru>Lundraco</span></a><br><b><span id=Guru>Guru</span></b><br><span id=notbold>18 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [5.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Quite often I have found myself using my cleric to pacify, especially in LDoN groups. Following are a few tips.<br><br>First off, I played a ranger for a few years--surprisingly, I have found that a few ranger tricks have helped me to pacify.<br><br>1. First and foremost, keep in mind that the single-target versions of Pacify are not Line-of-Sight spells. Further, if you are far enough away/out of the NPC's line of sight, there is a very good chance that you will not incur aggro on a resist. Therefore, I prefer to take over pacification duties if the group is without a paladin, rather than relying on Bard or Enchanter songs and spells.<br><br>2. The F9 viewchange. Make use of the F9 key to change your view to see around corners. 3 quick taps on F9, rightclick for mouselook, target your mob and pacify. 3 more taps to return to first person view. F9 can also help you to bypass those annoying cobwebs in dungeons that prevent you from targetting.<br><br>3. Bind Sight/Shifting Sight. If grouped with a Ranger, Wizard or Enchanter, one of these classes can help you in your pacification. Bind Sight and Shifting Sight will allow your partner to bind their point of view to the targeted NPC. from there, they can target a new NPC, recast, and bind anew. Remember the F9 key when doing this, too. So far as I know, there is no range limit to this spell as long as the next NPC is within casting range of your <i>current</i> point of view. I have sat at the bank in Firiona Vie and bound my sight all the way to the Swamp of No hope zone, jumping from NPC to NPC. (side note for Rangers, Enchanters, and Wizards--the sight binding spells are also useful in LDoN for other reasons, as long as the mobs are there for you to use--especially in regards to Named mobs. Rangers can Bind Sight to see exactly how many mobs are between the party and a Named mob. In the absence of a tracker, an Enchanter or Wizard can Shifting Sight to look for a Named--slow, and you may be balked by doors on occasion, but still doable.)<br><br>4. Timing. I have noticed over the past few weeks that the timer on Pacify spells seems to be broken. Keep this in mind, as I have mobs aggro <i>immediately</i> after successfully pacifying them. That said, it may be best to either have some macros set up to both keep the party updated and to tell your puller to assist off you to pull as soon as you are through pacifying. Either that, or pull yourself with a stun (which will give you time to dart back behind the melees so they can snag aggro asap).<br><br><i><span class=sm>Edited, Fri Jan 30 02:17:29 2004 by Lundraco</span class=sm></i></p>&nbsp;<br>Finndo Oberonson<br>Ranger of Tunare<br><br>"Know that ye do not exist 'til I meet thee. Risk my ire, and ye may not exist for long after that."</td></tr>
