<tr><td colspan=2><ul>
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td>
	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=/cgi-bin/mrate.pl name=f1072745772238362647>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=classes2.html?class=7&mid=1072745772238362647>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=classes2.html?class=7&mid=1072745772238362647>AHAHAH i like gorilla's</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes2.html?class=7&mid=1072745772238362647#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Mon, Dec 29th 7:56 PM 2003</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=144460><span id=Sage>Kareasint</span></a><br><b><span id=Sage>Sage</span></b><br><span id=notbold>18 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.13]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Clerics can Melee rather well at the upper levels. We have two main spells that allow us to fight well. The first is the Hammer Line. You cast it once when you log on and have a no rent hammer for use. The weapon has a Delay depending on the spell level that summoned it and damage will vary on which spell you use. This hammer will also have a 150 Point DD proc which can crit blast depending on your SCF/FoM skill. DEX is highly important for a hammer using Cleric as this determines procs.<br><br>The Second spell is the Yaulp Line. Yaulp V/VI will grant a number of things including mana regeneration (great for indoor areas), ATT increase, Haste, and DEX. This will give you a better chance to hit, the ability to hit more often and more procs off the hammer.<br><br>Now for the bad news. Yaulp V is not available until level 56. And the Hammer spells below 56th level have a poor delay.<br><br>So, to answer your first question, yes, Clerics can do other usefull stuff besides healing but they only become effective at it after 56th level. Stuns are available for use to disrupt casting and I recommend you save it for mobs that like to heal themselves.<br><br>The answer to the second question is yes. Spell components cost a lot of money depending on what you are buying. You buy them for:<br><br>1. Symbols and HP buffs (after 44th level). The Cleric has three main buff lines. AC, HP and Symbols (more HPs). Symbols will require you to have a spell component to cast them. At 44th level, you get the first combined line spell, Temperance. This does all three lines at once and uses a Peridot (10PP 5GP is teh cheapest you can get these for). Peridots will become your main spell component after 44th level. All buff spells after this use peridots. The group spells will use less peridots and mana than casting the individual version.<br><br>2. Death Pact spells. This is a chance for someone who dies to receive a heal and be kept alive. There are two spells. Death Pact is level 51 and uses a Pearl as its component. Divine Intervention is level 60 and uses two Emeralds (26PP).<br><br>3. Banishment of Shadows - level 60 spell. This is useful only on lower level Undead mobs. The targeted mob gets a save vs magic, but if it fails, it is gone. There will not even be a corpse to loot. It uses one Star Ruby.<br><br>4. Imbue spells - At level 29, the cleric gains the ability to imbue a gem based on their diety. Brell Clerics use Rubies. Mith Marr use Diamonds, etc. These imbued gems are used to make racial armor. The Cleric also gets one more imbue spell at 64th level, but this will cost you a Metallic Liquid and a Raw Diamond (Planes of Power spell).</p>&nbsp;<br>Kareasint Deathbane<br>Archon of Brell<br>Figment - Terris Thule</td></tr>
